why

The issue you're experiencing is a "double free." This happens when you try to free the same memory block more than once. The culprit lies in the `operator*` method, where you return a new `Array` object by value.

When an `Array` object is destroyed (when it goes out of scope), its destructor is called, which deletes the memory allocated for `arr_`. Since the `Array` class does not have a copy constructor or an assignment operator defined, the default ones provided by the compiler are used. The default copy constructor and assignment operator perform shallow copies, which means they copy the pointer `arr_` but not the memory it points to. When the temporary object created in `operator*` (as `new_arr`) is returned by value, its copy is made, and when the temporary object is destroyed, it deletes `arr_`. Then, when the copied object is destroyed (at a later time, such as at the end of `main`), it attempts to delete the same memory again, causing a double free.

To fix this, you need to implement the Rule of Three (or Rule of Five in C++11), which entails providing a copy constructor, assignment operator, and destructor to ensure proper copying and destruction of resources.

Here is an example of how you could implement this:

```cpp
class Array {
    // ... (rest of your class definition)

    // Copy constructor
    Array(const Array& other) {
        x_ = other.x_;
        y_ = other.y_;
        z_ = other.z_;
        int size = x_ * y_ * z_;
        arr_ = new uint32_t[size];
        std::copy(other.arr_, other.arr_ + size, arr_);
    }

    // Copy assignment operator
    Array& operator=(const Array& other) {
        if (this != &other) { // Self-assignment check
            delete[] arr_; // Free the existing resource
            x_ = other.x_;
            y_ = other.y_;
            z_ = other.z_;
            int size = x_ * y_ * z_;
            arr_ = new uint32_t[size];
            std::copy(other.arr_, other.arr_ + size, arr_);
        }
        return *this;
    }
};
```

With the copy constructor and copy assignment operator defined, the `Array` objects are properly copied, which includes duplicating the memory they manage, and thus, each `Array` object will manage its own separate block of memory. This will prevent the double free error and ensure that each `Array` instance cleans up its own resources when it is destroyed. 

Note that the Rule of Five also involves defining a move constructor and move assignment operator in addition to the ones already mentioned. Since implementing all these special member functions can be non-trivial and error-prone, it is often better to use smart pointers (`std::unique_ptr` or `std::shared_ptr`) along with STL containers (`std::vector`) which automatically handle resource management. If your class does not need to support copy semantics, you can delete the copy constructor and copy assignment operator to prevent copying altogether.

